  "text": "It is important to note that sedative agents may produce false-positive effects on the acetic acid-induced writhing response test [CITATION_1] . In this context, we used the rota-rod test to evaluate whether the antinociceptive effect of NOSH-aspirin upon acetic acid-induced writhing response might be due to an unspecific effect on motor coordinance. Importantly, NOSH-aspirin (150 lmol/kg, p.o.) did not change locomotor activity in all evaluated times. As a positive control, Diazepam produced significant motor impairment (Fig. 3) .",
